WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.880
Hi everyone, I'm Mika. I'm a software developer at Stanford University and I'm

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:10.280
going to be telling you about a set of tools and templates that me and my

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:15.440
collaborators have been developing to help improve data sharing. Imagine you're

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.719
a researcher and you've painstakingly created a high-value data set. For

00:00:19.719 --> 00:00:23.040
example, maybe you've taken body measurements from hundreds of penguins

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:27.440
and some people know what's going. So now you want to share your data with the

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:31.840
world. And you might want to do that in a way that follows guidelines that are

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:37.360
known as FAIR, making sure that your data is findable, accessible, interoperable,

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:42.439
and reusable. So how do you share your data? The easiest and most common thing

00:00:42.439 --> 00:00:46.320
that people do is just put a static file with your data somewhere people can

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:50.240
access, like a GitHub repo. And this is really quick and easy to do, but it

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:53.240
doesn't provide much support for your audience. If they want to look at your

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:57.240
data, they have to clone your repo or download the file, figure out what's

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:01.439
going on in there, and do any visualization that they might want to do

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:06.800
manually themselves. And I bet many of us can relate to the frustrating

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.000
experience of opening someone else's data spreadsheet and being like,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.680
what on earth is going on here? So on the other hand, you could put in a lot of

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:20.879
time and effort into making a custom repository, like maybe a database with an

00:01:20.879 --> 00:01:25.559
API, and you can make a custom website or a Shiny app with fancy visualizations.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:29.879
And all the stuff would be super helpful for your users, but a ton of work for you.

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:34.639
So personally, I've done both of these things many times for different projects,

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:38.440
and I wanted to help researchers and other people who manage data get the

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:42.040
best of both worlds. So I'll be telling you about how to create a data page,

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:46.160
which is basically a website for your data that's both easy to make and has a

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:50.959
lot of rich features that make it easy to use. So what are the components of a

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:55.599
data page? First off, you use the Redivis data platform to store your data set,

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:00.639
which for free immediately means that your data is versioned. And then you use

00:02:00.639 --> 00:02:05.559
our custom data pages Corda format to connect to this data to a Corda website

00:02:05.559 --> 00:02:10.119
that you can configure and customize. At the center of this website are

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:14.479
interactive visualizations created using Observable. So also you can add ggplot

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:19.279
or whatever other visualizations you want. And all this results in a static

00:02:19.279 --> 00:02:23.080
website so it can be hosted on GitHub pages, but it has rich interactive

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:27.440
functionality. I'm going to walk you through more concretely the steps you

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:32.039
would follow to spin up a new data page. To get started, all you would need to do

00:02:32.039 --> 00:02:37.080
is use the data page GitHub template repo to create your own repo. And this

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:42.119
gives you a template Corda website that uses our custom data pages Corda

00:02:42.119 --> 00:02:47.479
project type and format. And you then customize this website by adding

00:02:47.479 --> 00:02:51.440
information and formatting specific to your project and connecting it to the

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:56.440
Redivis table with your data. What do you get from doing all this? You get a

00:02:56.440 --> 00:03:01.520
website. The home page of your data page introduces your data set and features

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:05.800
these automatically created interactive visualizations. So this means that users

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:10.720
can get a feel for your data right away. And you can customize this through

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:15.479
configuration, through like YAML variables, or by adding like any custom

00:03:15.479 --> 00:03:21.600
content you want, or by swapping out these templated visualizations. And a

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:25.399
major area of focus for us is adding more configurability and more types of

00:03:25.399 --> 00:03:31.360
visualizations for you. In addition to the home page, other pages include the

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.479
data page where there's an embedded table browser inserted through a custom

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:39.320
shortcode. So users who might want to actually look at your data in more

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:46.320
detail can use this browser to preview your data and your metadata. Even more

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:50.119
involved users can go to the analysis page to see an automatically generated

00:03:50.119 --> 00:03:54.000
code snippet that tells them how to access the data directly from R or from

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.880
Python. And then finally on the about page you can edit all this YAML to add

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.600
links, to add citation information, and then you can add whatever content you

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:09.119
want. And of course since this whole thing is a Corda website you can add

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:12.759
other pages, you can customize the styling, and use all the amazing features

00:04:12.759 --> 00:04:19.679
that Corda now has and will have in the future. If you go to datapages.github.io

00:04:19.679 --> 00:04:24.160
you'll see a gallery of the different data pages we've made and find out how

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:29.920
to get started with making your own. Thank you.

